es and no range-based query --> Map O(1)\n        2. Geospatial Index --> If you are playing with location data, propose geospatial index.\n        3. Inverted Index --> If you need a read-heavy database.\n        5. Log Structured Merge Trees --> If you need a write-heavy database.\n        5. B+Tree --> your default in interviews.\n               a. If you are need indexes on multiple columns as they are always queried together - Composite Indexes work \n                 where both indexes can either show equality (birth country) or range-based (born year)\n               b. If you need to get complete data using index and don't want to query all the columns, covering index works\n                   CREATE INDEX ON TABLE(Index1, Index2) INCLUDE (<columnNames which completes the information>).\n                   Remember column names needs to be very less as it could increase index size. If it is more, better to query the table itself using index filters.\n\nHash Index - (Redis)\n    1. WRITE PATTERN - \n              a. A write gets persisted to in-memory cache and WAL log. At certain intervals, we make a immutable copy of the in-memory cache \n                  and WAL and clear the existing WAL. \n              b. Then we create a snapshot of the immutable in-memory cache's copy and delete the immutable copy as well as the WAL copy.\n   2.  READ PATTERN = \n             a. It just reads from the in-memory cache. If it is not present, cache miss.\n   3. The above pattern helps to recover Redis from cache.\n \n\nLog Structured Merge Trees as Index (DynamoDB + Cassandra)\n     1. WRITE PATTERN - \n             a. A write actually gets persisted in in-memory data structure called memtable and a WAL in the disk. \n             b. When the memtable reaches a fixed size, a copy of the memtable is created which can accept only read \n                 but no writes (called immutable memtable) and the original memtable is cleared.\n             c. Additionally, we also create a copy of the WAL which accepts no write but only reads and clear the original WAL.\n             d. Then we create a snapshot of the immutabe memtable in the disk (called SSTable) and delete the copy of the WAL.\n     2. READ PATTERN - \n             a. A read actually goes through the original memtable (which accepts both reads and writes)\n             b. The immutable memtable (which accepts reads but no writes)\n             c. The snapshot in the disk.\n     3. LSM is efficient for heavy writes but has poor reads latency.\n     4. It has no update policy. That means if a new update to the record comes, it is entered as a new entry in memtable and WAL\n          and snapshot (SSTable)\n\n\nGeoSpatial Index - (Redis + ElasticSearch)\n     1. There are 3 types of Indexes - QuadTrees, R+Trees and GeoHashing.\n     2. QuadTrees and R+ Trees are like Red-Black or AVL Trees which follows binary tree structure and on every new element, it has to re-balance itself.\n         These are useful in situations where the locations are uneven distributed\n     3. On the other hand, GeoHashing follows O(1) complexity. It also follows the same logic of QuadTrees or R+ Trees on further dividing a region, but \n         it stores every location as a hash map. These are useful in even distribution.\n\n\nInverted Index for Search Optimized Database (Elastic Search + Redis) -\n    1. They are useful to find list of data given a search string.\n    2. It works by using the concept of Inverted index where it breaks the statement into each word (1 word = 1 token) and \n        stem the word (such as runs or running becomes run) . \n    3. It then maps the word 'run' to the statement. So when the user searches with the string 'running', \n        it returns all the statements mapped to the word 'run'.\n\n\nThere are 5 ways of scaling database - \n    1. Vertical Scaling - Give interviewers the simplest option \n    2. Proper Indexes for Read and Batch Operations to Writes or Asynchronous writes to reduce IOP\n    3. Sharding - where we separate table data into multiple database servers based on column (2 or more tables in different databases based on some column)\n    4. Partitioning -  where we separate table data in the same database server \n        Horizontal partitioning: Same columns, fewer rows per partition.\n        Vertical partitioning: Same rows, fewer columns per partition.\n    5. Replicas - creating master/slave replica of the table data in multiple database servers\n\nSharding Concept in Relational Database -\n    1. It is a horizontal scaling concept of mapping the database nodes to store a subset of user's information. \n    2. For example, if there exists a database with 100 user's information, we can divide the database into 5 database nodes\n        where node A can accept user's 0-19 request, node B can accept user's 20-39 request and so on.\n    3. It helps to scale the requests to different database nodes each containing 200 user's information instead of \n        hitting just 1 database node with 1000 user's information. \n    4. What happens if every node starts receiving more TPS than required ? We can introduce another node to take the load\n       of other nodes. However, in doing so, the request served by 1 node will now go to another node and so the data will also need to migrate.\n    5. First, We need to understand how does each node know which request to serve ? We can use the concept of hashing.\n    6. Say we if we use a hashing algorithm on the request such as `Hash(user-id) % number of nodes` \n       where we each request knows which nodes to go. \n    7. If we add an extra node, user 18 will now be served by node B and data will need to be moved. \n       This will make a cascading effect across all nodes. So, it adds an overhead every-time an extra node is added.\n    8. What if we position nodes in an uniform space and if a node gets added or removed, the other nodes don't need to move.\n       For example, if we apply hashing such as `Hash(user-id) % (2^32)`, \n        every node will receive a position in the spectrum of 0 to 2^32 - 1. Say Node A received a position 10, node B received 50.\n    9. Now if a request comes for user and if we apply the same hashing algorithm such as `Hash(user-id) % (2^32)` and the \n        result is less than 10, node A can take care of it or if the result is less than 50, node B can take care of it. \n        If the result is more than 50, node A can take care of it.\n    10. Now if a new node comes, only neighbor's data needs to be shifted rather than having a cascading effect.\n    11. This is called consistent hashing in a uniform fixed space.\n    12. To avoid having non uniform load, we can have replicas of the nodes. Every node in the hash ring can communicate with each other on the health. \n           If few replicas of a node dies, we can create replicas of other node to distribute load.\n\nMore about Sharding -\n    1. A good shard key is the one that have lots of unique values (such as user_id) to avoid uneven load \n        and a query on the database should always hit 1 shard (try to avoid cross-shard calls).\n    2. If you create a shard on country name and your users are skewed towards 1 country, that shard is likely to get hit more.\n        On the other hand, query on user_id as shard key will always hit 1 shard.\n    3. 3 types of Sharding - \n         1. Range based shard (User 1-10M in shard1, User 10M-20M in shard2)\n         2. Hash-based Sharding (the above concept)\n         3. Directory based sharding (User_id to shard_id) \n \n\n\n\n\n",
