      "text": "APPLICATION LAYER COMMUNICATION PROTOCOLS CORE CONCEPTS\n\n\nHTTP Communication Protocols which uses TCP as Transport Layer (4) protocol -\n    1. RESTFUL HTTP communication - \n        a. For every HTTP client request, there will be a HTTP server response. Post that transaction, the connection will be closed\n        b. These requests/responses are stateless and independent of each other\n        c. Useful for basic CRUD Operations.\n    2. Fixed Polling (Variant of RESTFUL communication) -\n        a. The client makes a HTTP request always after a fixed interval. \n        b. The server responds to the request irrespective of data being present and closes the connection.\n        c. Similar to REST, the requests/responses are stateless and independent of each other.\n        d. Examples - periodic updates regarding stock, facebook feed, etc.\n    3. Long Polling (Variant of RESTFUL communication) -\n        a. The client makes a HTTP request whenever it wants to. \n        b. The server keeps the connection open until it has the data, reply back and closes the connection.\n        c. Similar to REST, the requests/responses are stateless and independent of each other.\n        d. Examples - Real time updates regarding stock, facebook feed, etc.\n    4. Adaptive Polling (Variant of Fixed Polling) -\n        a. The client makes a HTTP request in non-periodic intervals. The intervals are decided on factors such as server conditions such as load.\n        b. The server responds to the request irrespective of data being present and closes the connection.\n        c.  Similar to REST, the requests/responses are stateless and independent of each other.\n        d.  Examples - non-periodic updates regarding stock, facebook feed, etc.\n    5. Server Sent Event Communication -\n       a. Client sents a HTTP request and server sends a HTTP response stating that the connection will be open for a longer time.\n       b. The communication only happens from server to client at that point of time.\n       c. The server keeps on notifying the client with new updates.\n       d. Useful for Live updates, new twitter feeds or new facebook posts or event-driven notifications\n    6. Web Socket Communication - \n       a. This is bi-directional HTTP communication between server and clients where the connection is open for long. \n       b. For 1 communication from client, there can be X number of communication from servers (similar to SSE)\n       c. However for 1 communication from server, there can also be X number of communication from clients. (opposite of b)\n       d. Useful for real time chats or collaborative writing or online game.\n       e. It uses JSON format for exchanging data.\n\n\nHTTP/2 Communication Protocols which uses TCP as Layer 4 protocol -\n    1. google Remote Procedure Call -\n       a. This is exactly similar to the functioning of Web Socket Communication but it follows HTTP/2 protocol rather than HTTP protocol\n       b. However, it uses Protobuf as the format for exchanging data (.proto) --> Ex. Perfetto project\n       c. It is widely used between micro-services communication and not communication between server/clients (real-time chats) because\n          browser does not support HTTP/2 protocol as well as does not understand Protobuf communication\n           (there are alternatives such as gRPC-web but is not trusted in the industry yet)  \n\n\nUDP Communication Protocols -\n   1. Web Real Time Communication (WebRTC)\n      a. This is useful for clients communicating with other clients using UDP protocol for video calling, media transfer, etc.\n      b. The client1 makes a WebSocket Connection (HTTP) or gRPC connection (HTTP/2) with a signalling server.\n      c. The client2 also makes a WebSocket Connection (HTTP) or gRPC connection (HTTP/2) with a signalling server.\n      d. Client 1 sends an SDP (Session Description Protocol) offer to the signaling server via the WebSocket/gRPC connection established by Client1.\n      e. The Signalling Server sends the SDP offer to the Client2 via the WebSocket/gRPC connection established by Client2.\n      f. The Client2 receives the SDP offer and prepares the SDP answer (yes/no) and sends to the signaling server.\n      g. The Client1 receives the SDP answer from the signalling server.\n      h. If the answer is yes, both client1 and client2 starts preparing the ICE candidate with an intent to find the best network path for their WebRTC (UDP) connection.\n      i. The ICE candidate contains information about their IP addresses and ports.\n      j. Client1 and Client2 both sends their ICE candidate to the signalling server and \n         signalling server forwards each other requests to each other via WebSocket/gRPC connection established by them.\n      k. Once they receive each other's ICE candidate, they uses STUN (Session Traversal Utilities for NAT) to establish a WebRTC connection between them.\n      l. Once the connection is made, they can send video/audio over the WebRTC connection.\n      m. WebRTC uses UDP as the Layer 4 protocol. \n\n\nGuidelines to use communication protocol - \n     1. REST API or Fixed Polling - If you don't need Latency sensitive\n     2. SSE - If you need high latency but no bi-directional communication.\n     3. WebRTC - f you need high latency and bi-directional communication for audio/video\n     4. Web Socket/gRPC - If you need high latency and bi-directional communication\n",
      "fontSize": 40.8487314062977,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "APPLICATION LAYER COMMUNICATION PROTOCOLS CORE CONCEPTS\n\n\nHTTP Communication Protocols which uses TCP as Transport Layer (4) protocol -\n    1. RESTFUL HTTP communication - \n        a. For every HTTP client request, there will be a HTTP server response. Post that transaction, the connection will be closed\n        b. These requests/responses are stateless and independent of each other\n        c. Useful for basic CRUD Operations.\n    2. Fixed Polling (Variant of RESTFUL communication) -\n        a. The client makes a HTTP request always after a fixed interval. \n        b. The server responds to the request irrespective of data being present and closes the connection.\n        c. Similar to REST, the requests/responses are stateless and independent of each other.\n        d. Examples - periodic updates regarding stock, facebook feed, etc.\n    3. Long Polling (Variant of RESTFUL communication) -\n        a. The client makes a HTTP request whenever it wants to. \n        b. The server keeps the connection open until it has the data, reply back and closes the connection.\n        c. Similar to REST, the requests/responses are stateless and independent of each other.\n        d. Examples - Real time updates regarding stock, facebook feed, etc.\n    4. Adaptive Polling (Variant of Fixed Polling) -\n        a. The client makes a HTTP request in non-periodic intervals. The intervals are decided on factors such as server conditions such as load.\n        b. The server responds to the request irrespective of data being present and closes the connection.\n        c.  Similar to REST, the requests/responses are stateless and independent of each other.\n        d.  Examples - non-periodic updates regarding stock, facebook feed, etc.\n    5. Server Sent Event Communication -\n       a. Client sents a HTTP request and server sends a HTTP response stating that the connection will be open for a longer time.\n       b. The communication only happens from server to client at that point of time.\n       c. The server keeps on notifying the client with new updates.\n       d. Useful for Live updates, new twitter feeds or new facebook posts or event-driven notifications\n    6. Web Socket Communication - \n       a. This is bi-directional HTTP communication between server and clients where the connection is open for long. \n       b. For 1 communication from client, there can be X number of communication from servers (similar to SSE)\n       c. However for 1 communication from server, there can also be X number of communication from clients. (opposite of b)\n       d. Useful for real time chats or collaborative writing or online game.\n       e. It uses JSON format for exchanging data.\n\n\nHTTP/2 Communication Protocols which uses TCP as Layer 4 protocol -\n    1. google Remote Procedure Call -\n       a. This is exactly similar to the functioning of Web Socket Communication but it follows HTTP/2 protocol rather than HTTP protocol\n       b. However, it uses Protobuf as the format for exchanging data (.proto) --> Ex. Perfetto project\n       c. It is widely used between micro-services communication and not communication between server/clients (real-time chats) because\n          browser does not support HTTP/2 protocol as well as does not understand Protobuf communication\n           (there are alternatives such as gRPC-web but is not trusted in the industry yet)  \n\n\nUDP Communication Protocols -\n   1. Web Real Time Communication (WebRTC)\n      a. This is useful for clients communicating with other clients using UDP protocol for video calling, media transfer, etc.\n      b. The client1 makes a WebSocket Connection (HTTP) or gRPC connection (HTTP/2) with a signalling server.\n      c. The client2 also makes a WebSocket Connection (HTTP) or gRPC connection (HTTP/2) with a signalling server.\n      d. Client 1 sends an SDP (Session Description Protocol) offer to the signaling server via the WebSocket/gRPC connection established by Client1.\n      e. The Signalling Server sends the SDP offer to the Client2 via the WebSocket/gRPC connection established by Client2.\n      f. The Client2 receives the SDP offer and prepares the SDP answer (yes/no) and sends to the signaling server.\n      g. The Client1 receives the SDP answer from the signalling server.\n      h. If the answer is yes, both client1 and client2 starts preparing the ICE candidate with an intent to find the best network path for their WebRTC (UDP) connection.\n      i. The ICE candidate contains information about their IP addresses and ports.\n      j. Client1 and Client2 both sends their ICE candidate to the signalling server and \n         signalling server forwards each other requests to each other via WebSocket/gRPC connection established by them.\n      k. Once they receive each other's ICE candidate, they uses STUN (Session Traversal Utilities for NAT) to establish a WebRTC connection between them.\n      l. Once the connection is made, they can send video/audio over the WebRTC connection.\n      m. WebRTC uses UDP as the Layer 4 protocol. \n\n\nGuidelines to use communication protocol - \n     1. REST API or Fixed Polling - If you don't need Latency sensitive\n     2. SSE - If you need high latency but no bi-directional communication.\n     3. WebRTC - f you need high latency and bi-directional communication for audio/video\n     4. Web Socket/gRPC - If you need high latency and bi-directional communication\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
