      "originalText": "SERVER CORE CONCEPTS\n\nWhat happens when you type amazon.com/google.com ?\n   1. Browser looks for data in the browser DNS cache <--> Website/Domain Name : IP Address \n    2. If it does not find, it checks Operating System DNS cache.\n    3. If it does not find, it checks Router DNS cache.\n    4. If it does not find, it forwards the request to Internet Service Provider DNS  server.\n    5. If it does not find, it forwards the request to Root DNS Server and then to Top Level Domain DNS Server\n    6. Once finally found in the DNS,  the browser receives the IP Address of the server.\n    7. The browser tries to create a HTTPS connection with the web server.\n    8. The webserver acknowledges the request and send the HTML content as the response.\n    9. The browser parses the response and download/cache the static page.\n\nCompute Server Throughput vs Storage Server Throughput vs IOPS -\n   1. Compute Server is where the database engine resides - All in memory and does not persist restart\n   2. Storage Server is where the disk actually resides.\n   3. Compute Server is connected to Storage Server using a network cable whose throughput is called \n        Compute Server throughput.\n   4. Storage Server throughput is the amount of data that server can carry to read/write from the disk.\n   5. IOPS is the number of random operations that Storage Server needs to do per sec.\n   6. Throughput = IOPS * Block Size\n   7. While throughput can be calculated via IOPS, block size may differ with respect to what data we are reading. Hence a storage server should have\n       both IOPS and throughput provided. Either of them or both of them can be a limiting factor.\n   6. Question - If a query and page lookup is 16KB each and Compute Server throughput is 594 MiB/s and \n       Storage Throughput is 125 MiB/s with 3K IOPS/sec, can the system handle 20K reads/sec ?\n          a. 1 query and 1 page lookup equates to 32KB per read. 2 operations means 2 IOPS per read.\n          b. So, 20K reads/sec means 40K IOPS/sec [beats 3K IOPS/sec]\n          c. Storage Throughput = 40K IOPS * 32KB =  1,250 MiB/s [which beats both Storage and Compute Server throughput]\n\nRegionalization of Database and Server - \n   1. Database can be regionalized by sharding the database \n     based on close proximity of nearest data center and user_location\n   2. UserA who lives in Asia can access the shard placed close to Asia whereas\n      UserB who lives in Europe can access the shard place close to Europe.\n   3. Thereby, a centralized server will have to maintain a map in another distributed system\n       which maps to user id to its respective shard.\n   4. However, if the centralized server is located close to Europe, the latency to serve europe's \n      user_request would be much lesser as compared to Asia's user_request.\n   5. Hence, now we need to regionalize the server.\n   6. When multiple instances of server are deployed, on the basis of their availability zones, every one\n      of them is registered to DNS with different sub-domain but same domain name.\n   7. For example - API-asia.amazon.com points to a server which is deployed in ASIA \n      whereas API-europe.amazon.com points to a server which is deployed in Europe.\n      However, the main URL exposed to public would be API.amazon.com\n   8. So, now when a user in Asia makes a request on API.amazon.com/GET, \n      DNS will receive the request and also fetch client's user location.  \n      Based on geo-based DNS routing protocol (not done dive deep), it will figure out that the request needs \n      to be forwarded to API-asia.amazon.com, which is a server deployed in ASIA and \n      knows about its nearest data center close to Asia. \n   9. For validation, it will check the map in the distributed system to find the respective shard of that user,'\n      which will be its nearest data center.\n   10. What happens if the user in Asia moves to Europe and makes a request on API.amazon.com/GET\n   11. The DNS will receive the request and fetch the user's current location. Based on geo-based DNS routing protocol\n       it will figure out that the request needs to be forwarded to API-europe.amazon.com. \n   12. However, on checking the map in the distributed system, it will find the shard location to be in Asia.\n        So, the europe server will need to forward the request to asia server using the DNS API-asia.amazon.com\n   13. This will also increase the latency to serve the user request. If the europe server sees that the request\n        for the user has increased consistently from Europe, the practical approach would be to create replicas of the shard\n       with shard serving the most write request as the master and others are slave (read)\n   14. Remember, we used server as the external endpoint to our system. Ideally, it would be a routing service (such as AWS API Gateway)\n\n\nCascading Failures in the Servers - \n   1. Say User --> ServerA --> ServerB --> Database. Suddenly, database hits a bottleneck and started serving less requests. As a result, ServerB is \n      affected and started returning more non-200 codes to ServerA which in turns sends non-200 code to the user. This leads to cascade of failures.\n   2. In this case, ServerB should maintain knowledge on the response codes from the server and its average response time. If it sees that the response\n       codes are increasing for non-200 or average response time is exceeding a certain threshold, ServerB should gradually lower its TPS and ultimately be 0.\n   3. At the same time, ServerA should also maintain a knowledge on the response codes from the server and its average response time. If it sees that the response\n      codes are increasing for non-200 (in this case, it would be 429 as requests are getting dropped) or average response time is exceeding a certain threshold, \n      ServerA should gradually lower its TPS and ultimately be 0.\n   4. However, ServerB should not accept any request from ServerA but at the same time keep on pinging the database.\n   5. Now when Database starts returning 200 codes or average response time starts to lower down, ServerB can gradually increase the TPS \n      such that it does not overwhelm the database.\n   6. Similarly, ServerA can also gradually increase the TPS such that it does not overwhelm ServerB.\n\n\nRetries for Server-Client Request -\n    1. We can have different retry strategy to retry a client request - \n    2. Normal Retry - where every client's request is retried after a fixed period of interval. This means if 5 clients makes a request at the same time and it fails,\n       the next retry of all the five clients would be at (T + fixed period)\n    3. Exponential backoff - where every client's request is retried after a exponential period of time. The math = initial delay * (2^N) where N is number of retries.\n       This means if 5 clients makes a request at the same time and it fails, the next retry would be at [1 * 2^0], the next retry would be 2 seconds, 4 seconds and so on.\n    4. Exponential backoff is more preferred as it will give the system more time to recover by exponentially increasing the retry period.\n    5. However, both of the retry strategy does not solve the problem where all of the 5 clients requests are retried at the same time. This is called \n       thundering herd problem.\n    6. Full Jitter with Exponential backoff - To solve this, we can add a bit of randomness to every client request while following the exponential backoff strategy.\n    7. The math for full jitter is random(0, 2^N) where where N is number of retries.\n    8. This means if 5 clients makes a request at the same time and it fails, the next retry would be random(0, 2^0) - so there is a high probability of all the requests getting\n        retried in 1 second. However, this will make more sense if we are retrying for the 4th time, then every client request would be random(0, 2^3) and the probability of \n        all requests being retried at the same time reduces.   \n\nDevice Native Push Notification Service -\n      a. Devices will have to register itself to the service and can disconnect.\n      b. These service will send a notification to the devices even if they are not connected.\n      c. Example - Apple Push Notification Service or Firebase Cloud Messaging\n\n\nCapture Data Change - \n     a. DynamoDB or any relational DB will have some triggers. Connect the triggers to some Event Stream which is immutable and persist the data.\n     b. If a DB does not have any triggers or direct connect to streams, then invest in \"reader/forwarder\" which continuously tails/watches the WAL \n         of the DB, parses messages which matches the trigger and forwards only matching ones to event streams .\n     b. Event Bridge acts as Publisher/Subscriber which will take the responsibility of -\n             1. Polling from the Event Stream\n             2. Do some Rule-based filtering \n             3. Write to subscribers based on rule-based filtering (multiple destinations such as SQS)\n                  or you can directly invoke an Lambda API.",
