      "text": "KEY TECHNOLOGIES\n\nAmazon RDS MySQL For Relational Database Selection\n   1. Storage:  64 TiB\n   2. Read/Write IOPS:  3K IOPS/second --> 2 IOPS per read and write (page + query)\n   3. Storage Throughput:   125 MiB/s  \n   4. Compute Throughput:  594 MiB/s \n\nDynamoDB (Read-Heavy Non-Relational Database)\n   1. Primary Key (Partition Key for equality and Sort Key for Range based query) is constant but schema/attributes can differ for every record.\n   2. Partition Key uses HashIndex whereas SortKey uses B+Tree Index.\n   2. Global Secondary Index is different Partition Key but same Sort Key. On the other hand, Local Secondary Index is same partition key but \n       different sort key.\n   3. DynamoDB Streams is used as Capture Database Change (CDC) for streaming events happening in DyanamoDB.\n   4. Cons  - Table-Joins/Complex Queries are expensive as compared to SQL\n   5. Storage:  Unlimited\n   6. Read/Write IOPS:  40K IOPS/second (3K IOPS/sec for every partition = 13 partitions)\n   7. Read Throughput: 156 MiB/s (40K × 4KB) Block Size for READ = 4KB\n   8. Write Throughput:  39 MiB/s (40K × 1KB)  Block Size for WRITE = 1KB\n\nCassandra (Write-Heavy Non-Relational Database)\n   1. Primary Key (Partition Key for equality and Clustering Key for Range based query) is constant but schema/attributes can differ for every record.\n   2. Primary Key uses Log Structured Merge Tree Index for write-heavy operations which makes reads slower.\n   3. Append only \n   3. Cons  - Table-Joins/Complex Queries are expensive as compared to SQL\n   4. Storage - 10TB\n   5. Write IOPS: 45K IOPS/sec and Read IOPS: 30K IOPS/sec\n   6. Read Throughput: 300 MiB/s\n   7. Write Throughput: 300 MiB/s   \n\nRedis - \n    1. It can act as a cache and lock in a distributed system.\n    2. It can act as a message broker such as SQS\n    3. It can act as a event driven pub/sub such as SNS\n    4. It can act as a rate limiter also.\n    5. It supports Inverted Indexes as well as GeoHashIndexes\n    6. Storage - 20GB-1TB\n    7. Read/Write IOPS: 100K IOPS/Sec\n    8. Read/Write Throughput: 1500MiB/sec (only in memory)\n\nAPI Gateways \n    1. Act as a single entry point to route your request to the correct microservice and return the response.\n    2. It support middle-ware such authentication, routing services, load balancer, rate limiting (limiting the request to exceed max TPS), \n        throttling traffic (queue the request if the rate limiting reached its max), etc\n    3. Use it when you have a micro-services architecture and don't use it when you have a simple client-server architecture \n       because routing service will only route the request to the single server.\n\nAmazon SQS (as a Message Broker)\n    1. Message Size: 256KB\n    2. Retention: 14 days\n    3. Standard Queue - No ordering but unlimited throughput. Under the hood, SQS scales indefinitely.\n    4. FIFO Queue - Ordering but 3000 messages/sec for 1 message group. You can have multiple groups in FIFO. \n        Under the hood, SQS scales finitely with every message group (shard based on message group) going to same shard.\n    5. SQS have retry mechanism, post which it goes to DLQ for investigation.\n\nAmazon SNS (as a PubSub)\n    1. Message Size: 256 KB\n    2. Retention: 23 days for retries only. Once consumed, it is deleted.\n    3. Standard Topics: No ordering but unlimited throughput. Under the hood, SNS scales indefinitely.\n    4.  FIFO Queue - Ordering but 3000 messages/sec for 1 topic. You can have multiple topic in FIFO. \n         Under the hood, SNS scales finitely with every message group (shard based on message group) going to same shard.\n    5. SNS retires for 23 days. So, the message needs to be sitting on a disk\n    6. Maximum of 5K subscribers\n\nAmazon Kinesis (Event Stream)\n   1. Message Size: 1MB (Record + Partition Key)\n   2. Retention: 365 days\n   3. Ordered with limited throughput --> 1000 shards max with each shard's write throughput of 1MB/sec and read throughput of 2MB/sec.\n   4. Each shard can have a maximum of 5 subscribers sharing 2M/sec\n   5. IOPS = Total throughput / Message Size of 1 KB = 3K IOPS/sec\n\nAmazon Kinesis Data Analytics (Event Stream Aggregator - Apache Flink)\n   1. RAM: 4GB\n   2. KDA also follows a two-step aggregation policy if there are too many shards to listen to.\n   3. Every shard in KDA listens to max amount of shards and aggregate in its own tumbling window and then provide the results to the top\n       KDA shard whose responsibility is to aggregate from all KDA shards.\n   \n\nElastic Search (Search Optimized Database)\n   1. Storage - 50 GB per shard (Max Shard - 1000)\n   2. Write: 5K docs/sec per shard (No fixed block size)\n   3. Read: 500 queries/sec per shard (No fixed block size)\n\nLambdas (Serverless Function)\n   1. Batch size is 10 for SQS\n   2. Batch size is 10K for Kinesis Streams\n",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "KEY TECHNOLOGIES\n\nAmazon RDS MySQL For Relational Database Selection\n   1. Storage:  64 TiB\n   2. Read/Write IOPS:  3K IOPS/second --> 2 IOPS per read and write (page + query)\n   3. Storage Throughput:   125 MiB/s  \n   4. Compute Throughput:  594 MiB/s \n\nDynamoDB (Read-Heavy Non-Relational Database)\n   1. Primary Key (Partition Key for equality and Sort Key for Range based query) is constant but schema/attributes can differ for every record.\n   2. Partition Key uses HashIndex whereas SortKey uses B+Tree Index.\n   2. Global Secondary Index is different Partition Key but same Sort Key. On the other hand, Local Secondary Index is same partition key but \n       different sort key.\n   3. DynamoDB Streams is used as Capture Database Change (CDC) for streaming events happening in DyanamoDB.\n   4. Cons  - Table-Joins/Complex Queries are expensive as compared to SQL\n   5. Storage:  Unlimited\n   6. Read/Write IOPS:  40K IOPS/second (3K IOPS/sec for every partition = 13 partitions)\n   7. Read Throughput: 156 MiB/s (40K × 4KB) Block Size for READ = 4KB\n   8. Write Throughput:  39 MiB/s (40K × 1KB)  Block Size for WRITE = 1KB\n\nCassandra (Write-Heavy Non-Relational Database)\n   1. Primary Key (Partition Key for equality and Clustering Key for Range based query) is constant but schema/attributes can differ for every record.\n   2. Primary Key uses Log Structured Merge Tree Index for write-heavy operations which makes reads slower.\n   3. Append only \n   3. Cons  - Table-Joins/Complex Queries are expensive as compared to SQL\n   4. Storage - 10TB\n   5. Write IOPS: 45K IOPS/sec and Read IOPS: 30K IOPS/sec\n   6. Read Throughput: 300 MiB/s\n   7. Write Throughput: 300 MiB/s   \n\nRedis - \n    1. It can act as a cache and lock in a distributed system.\n    2. It can act as a message broker such as SQS\n    3. It can act as a event driven pub/sub such as SNS\n    4. It can act as a rate limiter also.\n    5. It supports Inverted Indexes as well as GeoHashIndexes\n    6. Storage - 20GB-1TB\n    7. Read/Write IOPS: 100K IOPS/Sec\n    8. Read/Write Throughput: 1500MiB/sec (only in memory)\n\nAPI Gateways \n    1. Act as a single entry point to route your request to the correct microservice and return the response.\n    2. It support middle-ware such authentication, routing services, load balancer, rate limiting (limiting the request to exceed max TPS), \n        throttling traffic (queue the request if the rate limiting reached its max), etc\n    3. Use it when you have a micro-services architecture and don't use it when you have a simple client-server architecture \n       because routing service will only route the request to the single server.\n\nAmazon SQS (as a Message Broker)\n    1. Message Size: 256KB\n    2. Retention: 14 days\n    3. Standard Queue - No ordering but unlimited throughput. Under the hood, SQS scales indefinitely.\n    4. FIFO Queue - Ordering but 3000 messages/sec for 1 message group. You can have multiple groups in FIFO. \n        Under the hood, SQS scales finitely with every message group (shard based on message group) going to same shard.\n    5. SQS have retry mechanism, post which it goes to DLQ for investigation.\n\nAmazon SNS (as a PubSub)\n    1. Message Size: 256 KB\n    2. Retention: 23 days for retries only. Once consumed, it is deleted.\n    3. Standard Topics: No ordering but unlimited throughput. Under the hood, SNS scales indefinitely.\n    4.  FIFO Queue - Ordering but 3000 messages/sec for 1 topic. You can have multiple topic in FIFO. \n         Under the hood, SNS scales finitely with every message group (shard based on message group) going to same shard.\n    5. SNS retires for 23 days. So, the message needs to be sitting on a disk\n    6. Maximum of 5K subscribers\n\nAmazon Kinesis (Event Stream)\n   1. Message Size: 1MB (Record + Partition Key)\n   2. Retention: 365 days\n   3. Ordered with limited throughput --> 1000 shards max with each shard's write throughput of 1MB/sec and read throughput of 2MB/sec.\n   4. Each shard can have a maximum of 5 subscribers sharing 2M/sec\n   5. IOPS = Total throughput / Message Size of 1 KB = 3K IOPS/sec\n\nAmazon Kinesis Data Analytics (Event Stream Aggregator - Apache Flink)\n   1. RAM: 4GB\n   2. KDA also follows a two-step aggregation policy if there are too many shards to listen to.\n   3. Every shard in KDA listens to max amount of shards and aggregate in its own tumbling window and then provide the results to the top\n       KDA shard whose responsibility is to aggregate from all KDA shards.\n   \n\nElastic Search (Search Optimized Database)\n   1. Storage - 50 GB per shard (Max Shard - 1000)\n   2. Write: 5K docs/sec per shard (No fixed block size)\n   3. Read: 500 queries/sec per shard (No fixed block size)\n\nLambdas (Serverless Function)\n   1. Batch size is 10 for SQS\n   2. Batch size is 10K for Kinesis Streams\n",
