      "text": "COMMON PATTERN\n\nSCALING WRITES -\n\nScaling Writes for higher write throughput (more requests coming in - higher TPS)\n   1. Start with sharding the database with partition key which is unique.\n   2. [BATCH REQUESTS] If sharding them does not reduce the load to your expectations and LATENCY is not SENSITIVE\n          a. You can add them to message queues and process at your own speed and hit database at your comfort.\n          b. Aggregate multiple requests and hit database at a specific fixed interval (In-memory aggregation such as Event Processor)\n   3. If the write throughput is higher on a specific shard (Popular Ad), you can be further sharded into multiple instances by using -\n          a. Use compound keys as partition keys - user_id + <timestamp>\n          b. Add randomness to partition keys - user_id + random(0,10) to be distributes to multiple shards.\n    4. If the writes to the database keep on increasing, make a trade-off between rate-limiting or process them later (not latency sensitive).\n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where clients don't affect each other with high writes + high reads(Ad Click Analytics/ Monitoring System) \n    1. We can horizontally scale the service to increase the throughput which would involve making multiple database calls.\n    2. Bad because writing to DB for 1M clicks/ad can lead to max throughput and DB will stop responding and hence clicks will be lost.\n    3. Our requirement should be very simple - \n           a. Avoid hitting database for every click count and perform aggregation in memory.\n           b. For aggregation in memory, you need clicks for a single ad to be in same shard/server so that the aggregator can calculate \n               the count for that window and does not have to care about reading data from other shards.\n    4. We have multiple options - \n          a. SNS + SQS + Lambda + Database - If we take the FIFO approach, the throughput is 3K messages/sec. Even though we have 1 SNS + 1 SQS\n              for a single AD, clients will have operational burden to maintain this pair for every AD. Additionally, if 1 AD becomes hot (say 1M click/sec for a single ad)\n              you are gone.\n          b. DynamoDB Streams - You have to involve DynamoDB which will itself not able to handle 1M clicks/ad throughput which is roughly around\n              1 GB/sec (1 click = 1KB, hence 1M/sec * 1KB = 1GB/sec) \n          c. Kinesis + KDA - Kinesis have a max throughput of 1 GB/sec (1000 shards) which just matches the 1M clicks/sec. Here we need to make sure that partition key is ad_id\n              such that every click count for that ad goes into the same shard. Each KDA shard can listen to Kinesis stream shard which will have complete click count for the ads \n              in that Kinesis shards and it will aggregate them in memory for a fixed window and output to database.\n     5. How will we aggregate data for 1 day, 1 month or 1 year ?\n            a. We can have KDA output aggregations over a period of 1 hour to the database.\n            b. Post that, we can run cron job or aggregate when requested for a certain period.\n     6. What happens if the shard becomes hot due to popular user ? \n            a. If we are reading AD22, we can think of replicas or copying the same AD22 data in multiple shards (same data in different database servers)\n            b. If we are calculating the click count on AD22, hitting that 1 shard would be disaster. Hence, we can divide them into more shards by - \n                a. Compound keys as partition keys - 'Ad_id + timestamp' so that ('AD22 + 10PM')%2 = shard 5 is now getting hit to calculate click count.\n                b. Randomness in Partition keys - 'Ad_id + random(0, 10)' so that this ad can go to any of the shards.\n     7. What happens if you need Aggregation between ads ? (TopK Ads)\n           a. We can have CRON jobs calculating TopK periodically after Kinesis+KDA writes to the database. (OR)\n           b. Have 2 layer streaming architecture where 1st layer of Kinesis + KDA can aggregate per ad and then provide the hourly or monthly data from 1st KDA layer (all shards)\n               to just 1 shard of the 2nd KDA layer which will calculate the TopK and persist it. Similarly, we can do for monthly or daily.\n     8. For high reads during this pattern, focus on pre-computing the data as much as possible. If pre-computing fails, then compute at that instant (But call it out to interviewers)\n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Eventual Consistency + No-Conflict (Whatsapp/LiveComments)\n    1.  In LiveComments and Whatsapp GroupChats, all the instances are publisher and subscriber so that 1 message is broadcasted to all\n         other users in real time.\n    2. Use Pub/Sub mechanism - Select a nice topic and reason about publisher/subscriber. In Direct message, \n         the receiver is the subscriber and sender is the publisher.\n    3. Remember Pub/Sub does not persist message, so there is data loss. IF data loss is a requirement, think of fallback ways (inbox in whatsapp)\n    4. For high writes, focus on the above strategy of using a streaming layer.\n    5. Since users and servers both send message to each other, focus on bi-directional communication (web socket).\n\nHigh-frequency real time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Eventual Consistency + Conflict (Quip docs) -\n    1. Follow the protocol of upload and then download to resolve conflicts\n    2. Clients and server maintain data separately and server owns the responsibility of resolving the conflicts - \n           a.  Client 1 and Client 2 uploads its data to the server which routes it to Conflict Resolution Server\n           b. The server will compare the timestamp and resolve the conflict of making Client 1's chunk as the official copy.\n           c. Once the server publishes the message to Pub/Sub, it is broadcasted to all instances and the instances sends the information to clients.\n           d. Client 1 will compare and find the data's lastUpdatedTimestamp in its local DB is equal to that of server copy and won't do anything.\n           3. Client 2 will compare and find the chunk's lastUpdatedTimestamp in its local DB is less than that of server copy and will download the chunk.\n\nHigh-frequency real time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Strong Consistency  + Conflict (AuctionBidding) -\n    1. For high writes with strong consistency,use distributed lock to only have 1 winner request over other requests made at the same time.\n    2. Follow the principle of using Pub/Sub and broadcast to other server instances for the winning request.\n\n\nSCALING READS\n\nScaling Reads for higher read throughput (more requests coming in - higher TPS)\n    1. Replicas are useful for scaling reads as well as fault-tolerance in database.\n          1. Master replica will accept write/read and slave replicas only accepts reads. \n          2. If a new data gets written to master and services require strong consistency, then all replicas needs to be updated.\n                 a. If we require partial consistency, we can think of quorum in replicas (3/5 replica needs to be updated)\n                 b. If stale data is okay to accept, the read from any replica.\n                 c. If all replica is not updated or we didn't receive a quorum, direct the reads to master till replication is complete\n          3. Spawning a replica induces start-up time. Hence, we should depend upon monitoring system which would trigger the right time for spawning an instance.\n          4. Additionally, once a replica is spawned, it needs to be in sync with the master. Hence, those replicas needs to talk to master server (Gossip) to retrieve the in-memory state.\n          5. If reading from a replica changes its own in-memory state and that state needs to be synced with the master, it is same as salting a shard \n              because it becomes a problem of heavy write throughput on a specific shard. \n .  2. Imagine there is 100K requests per second and there is a cache miss, all 100K will hit database with the hot row (Thundering herd). In such cases, \n          a. Combine similar requests into a single request and then hit the database to retrieve the entry. For a hot entry, this is particularly useful. \n          b. In-case the latency is not sensitive, for all the thundering herd requests, you can add jitter/randomness to spread them and avoid hitting database at the same time,\n   3. In case of hot or viral entry (celebrity problems),\n          a. As mentioned above, you can combine multiple requests into a single request and hit the database. \n          b. In case you cannot combine them into a single request, you can persist the hot entry in a cache if spawning more replicas are challenging. Additionally to prevent the entry \n              from being deleted from cache, we can proactively keep updating the TTL or even create a new entry (cache versioning) if the entry gets modified.\n\nScaling Reads for latency sensitive \n    1. Pre-compute the list of data in a cache so that when users request, you don't have to compute a complex query in a database and instead retrieve pre-computed data \n        from cache. These are very helpful for cases such as Feed Generation.\n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where clients only reads and does not affect other clients \n    1. Always use Pub/Sub mechanism if you only want recent data (StockUpdate)\n         a. Only 1 publisher but multiple subscribers\n         b. All of the server will maintain SSE connection.\n    2. Pre-computed cache if you want list of data (PostFeed / NewsFeed/ PriceHistory)\n         a. As you paginate, keep on hitting the database, proactively sensed and initiated by the apps.\n         b. Simple HTTP request should suffice.\n\nHigh-reads which alters the in-memory state of instances (Distributed Rate Limiter/ Distributed Cache)\n     a. Increased GET operation requires a change in state of the instance. So, that GET is actually causing a write (LRU). Hence to distribute load, if you spawn more\n         instances, you need to synchronize between all those replicas. On the other hand, you can also choose to saltify that shard to distribute load. In both cases\n         you have to sync each other instances. That means it became a scaling write problem.\n     b. To replace a shard from the hash ring by another instance, you need an early trigger to spawn an instance and sync it with the deteriorating primary so that the\n         new instance is upto date with the deteriorating primary.\n     c. Now, once the primary reaches a bad state, the new one can take up its place in the hash ring\n\n\n\nMulti-Step Workflow (E-commerce)\n      1. All Orders looks like a finite state machine (Order Placed - Inventory Update - Payment - Confirmation)\n      2. All the state transitions for each order needs to be persisted in the event of crash\n      3. There could be multiple instances of the workers working for same state to transition an order to that state to new state. For example, multiple instances of the payment workers\n           will pick up the orders sitting in Payment state, talk to payment service, if succeeded, transition to confirmation state, where confirmation workers will confirm to the user\n          Else failed state where failure workers send a rejection email to users.\n\n\nLong Running Tasks \n     1. For tasks which require a lot of computational power and is a long running process, the server should put the task in a queue, update its database \n         and reply back to the client that is is ongoing.\n     2. A lambda worker (from multiple instances) will read from the queue, execute the task and update the server's database.\n     3. The server database can then notify the server that task has been completed, to which server can respond to the client. \n     4. Since we have bunch of lambda workers (stateless), we ideally should maintain a heartbeat mechanism so that we can spawn a new one but AWS handles auto-scaling.\n     5. You can also separate queues based on approximate task type (Generating a report takes 5 seconds where transcoding may take 1 hour)\n     6. For these 1 hour tasks, we may need to implement the multi-step-workflow - prefer server to own the responsibility of finite state machine for that job\n         and break the job into smaller parts for easy and shorter processing.\n\n\n     \n     ",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
