      "text": "COMMON PATTERN II\n\nCompeting for a single resource (Buying Tickets/Grocery Shopping/Auction Bidding)\n      1. If all the users are connected to the same server fighting for the same ticket seat, always start with application level locking (mutex for atomic operation).\n      2. If you don't want application level locking and comfortable with database level locking using a single transaction, there are 2 ways in SQL -\n              a. Optimistic concurrency control where you read the row which requires to be updated and extract the version of the row.\n                  Post that, you use version number to make UPDATE/DELETE/INSERT call and if the version number is different, the call is rejected.\n              b. Pessimistic concurrency control locks the row BEFORE reading the value and then proceed to update. It has a higher latency than the above.\n      3. If multiple users are connected to multiple servers, every server will contact the database once to buy the tickets and it can lead to double booking.\n          In such cases, we can have 2 options - \n              a. We can have strongly consistent distributed locks. Now, what if all the servers make a call to distributed locks at once for a very popular concert, \n                  we need to hit the distributed lock in a sequential manner so that 1 request can set the lock with TTL and other gracefully see that value and return.\n              b. Request all the servers to send the write call to an Ordered message broker specifically designed for that concert and that first one out will update the database\n                  and the others will update the same seat but the seat status could be 'RESERVED'.\n              c. Option b is less favorable because an event can become hot during runtime and we don't want to spin up a infrastructure and make code changes. Additionally, \n                  you have to maintain different seat status for a ticket because users may need some time to complete booking information. This seat status can be completely \n                  eliminated with distributed locks because a locking would entail it is reserved so that other users cannot see them. Once the user confirms the seat, the database\n                  is modified to complete.\n      4. In case where you need to update multiple databases (Debit/Credit between 2 accounts), prefer to lock in a fixed manner always irrespective of which account is sending the payment\n              a. If both the users are connected to same server and prefer application level tracking, remember you need to persist what you do so that you can recover from failure and proceed\n                  to database transaction in a fixed manner\n              b. If both the users are connected to different server, use distributed locks in a fixed manner\n              c. #a and #b will help in avoiding deadlock\n       5. Since now, we establish distributed lock as a mechanism to compete for a resource (strong consistency) when users are connected to different servers - \n              a. We can use distributed lock if the count of the resource is always 1. But this is not the case in majority of things \n                  such as grocery inventory (2 step action - reserve and purchase) or bidding for an item (1 step action - validate if bid is greater)\n              b. In such cases, we can use <item_id>:<count> --> This will be useful for total count of an item or bid price of an item.\n              c. For reservation, we can use <item_id_user_id_reserver>:<count>. In such cases, we need to update the total count of the item.\n              d. Step b and Step c needs to be atomic in nature.\n              e. In short, we are using cache as a lock interchangeably and DISTRIBUTED CACHE acts a source of truth which helps in reading faster \n        \n\nUpload a large file (>10MB) with resume-able upload/download \n    1. If the file to be uploaded is less than 10 MB, the backend server takes the responsibility of generating the pre-signed S3 URL and return to the app to upload\n        the file directly to S3.\n    2. However, if the file > 10MB (say 5 GB). The app takes the responsibility of splitting the large file using SPLIT command into smaller chunks say 5MB. \n        You can also use AWS Client SDK which will take care of stripping the large file into smaller chunks and generate the hash for the same.\n    3. The app will persist all of these chunks metadata in its local DB and make a request to server to upload this large file by providing all the chunk metadata.\n    4. The server will persist all the chunk metadata to the file-id in its DB and would provide pre-signed URL for all the chunks to the app.\n    5. If the requirement is to just upload the file without worrying about assembling the chunks, just start multi-part upload from S3 which will return the uploadID.\n            a. The app will start uploading the chunk to S3 and on completion, it will update its local and SERVER DB accordingly with status and timestamp\n                to avoid single point of failure if device crashes.\n            b. If the network connection breaks, the app knows till what chunk it uploaded and continue the upload.\n            c. Once the network resumes, the app will start uploading the remaining chunk to S3. Once it completes, it sends a request to server with updated chunk\n                 metadata and the server sends a completion request to S3 stating that upload is complete and successfully close the uploadID.\n            d. S3 takes the responsibility of consolidating the chunk to make it a bigger file.\n     6. If the requirement is to upload the file and take care of assembling the chunks in interest of storage savings, the server has to mimic like the multi-part upload.\n            a. Once the app sends file and chunk metadata, the server needs to spawn a sessionId and only return the pre-signed URL of the chunks which does not have \n                the hash in the global table.\n            b. For the chunks whose hash is present in the global table, just copy the S3 location URL to those chunks record. We are saving cost by \n                content-based chunking.\n            c. With content-based chunking, we now have to maintain the order of chunks so that when GET is called, we can return the S3 location URL in the proper\n                chronological order.\n            d. With multi-part upload, we can delete the chunk metadata once successfully uploaded to S3. But since we are mimicking the S3 multi-part upload, we need\n                to use File + Chunk Metadata as File's Manifest - very similar to Video Streaming's Manifest containing segments.\n       7.  To download the photo,  The app makes a request to server to provide the S3 URL of the file.\n       8. If it is uploaded via multi-part download, \n              a.  S3 does not know what part of the data has been downloaded.\n              b. The app maintains the local DB and specifies the range to be downloaded \n                   GET /large-file.zip\n                   Range: bytes=0-10485759  (first 10MB)\n        9. If it is uploaded via the server taking the responsibility of assembling, \n               a. the server provides a list of S3 URL in order and the app can prepare the local DB in its end and simply request download\n                b. Because of the order, it will feel like streaming.\n        10. If the local and server has FileCHUNKMETADATA table for every file, we can proceed with delta sync where we can identify which CHUNKS are NEW and which got\n          DELETED, so that only those can be updated across devices.\n\n\nVideo Streaming\n     1. Once the upload is complete and the microservice marks the status of Video Metadata as Completed,\n          the actual process of generating the video in different resolution starts (Calls Transcoding)\n     2. Transcoded performs the responsibilities for every new video -\n             a. It downloads the file from S3 and decode the video into its raw form.\n             b. It creates different resolution of the same video -\n                   1. Throw away pixels for a lower resolution via Sampling. You could have a high/low bitrate to adjust how those existing pixels look.\n                   2. Invent new pixels for a higher resolution via InterPolation. You could have a high/low bitrate to adjust how those new and existing pixels look.\n             c. Re-encodes the videos of different resolution.\n             d. Breaks them into smaller segments (segmentation) of usually 2 to 5 MB and uploads these segments to the S3.\n             e. Prepare a Quality-specific Manifest file which contains the correct sequence of these segments with file location and upload to S3. (Similar to FileChunkMetadata)\n             f. Prepare a Master Manifest file contains the list of Quality-specific Manifest file\n             d. It then persist the Master Manifest file S3 URL in DB.\n     3. Now when the app requests the server, it just provides the master manifest S3 URL location.\n     4. The app becomes the orchestrator and request CDN/S3 for master manifest file and depending upon the internet connection, it selects a quality\n          manifest file and then request the CDN/S3 to dowload the segments in a sliding window technique.\n     5. When the window shifts, it deletes the segments and download new segments. \n     6. As a result, it looks like the app is playing a movie disguised as playing a bunch of smaller segments .\n     7. Now, if the internet quality gets better, the app proactively requests the server to fetch a better quality video\n        and download segments of higher quality while playing lower quality video.\n    9. The app keeps a track of last segment downloaded for a lower quality and once the video reaches to that time, the app\n        switches to play the new segment of the higher quality. That's why it looks the video suddenly improved.\n   10. <VideoID>/\n                ├── master.m3u8                (The Master Manifest)\n                ├── 1080p/\n                │   ├── playlist.m3u8          (The 1080p Quality Manifest)\n                │   ├── segment_001.ts         (Actual video data)\n                │   ├── segment_002.ts\n                │   └── ...\n                ├── 720p/\n                │   ├── playlist.m3u8          (The 720p Quality Manifest)\n                │   ├── segment_001.ts\n                │   └── ...\n                └── 360p/\n                    ├── playlist.m3u8          (The 360p Quality Manifest)\n                    ├── segment_001.ts\n                    └── ...\n\nAuthentication\n     1. The two main pillars of security are Signing and Encryption. The principle followed is Signed-then-Encrypt\n     2. Signing a request means the receiver can validate if it is really the sender who claims to be the owner of the request\n         and has the data be compromised in the transit\n           a. It ensures authentication by validating the sender as the owner of the request.\n           b. It ensures integrity by validating has the data changed in the transit.\n           c. When Sender and Receiver first meet, the sender generates a private key and public key for signing and forwards the public key to the receiver. \n           d. Sender hash the request using SHA_256 --> HS = SHA_256(request) and signs the hash using their private key (RSA algorithm) \n               SS = Sign(HS, PrivateKey) and adds a new field to the request called \"Signature\" {\"senderId\": \"\", \"data\": \"value\", \"Signature\":  \"SS\"}\n           e. Receiver receives the request and hashes the same using SHA_256 without the Signature field. HR = SHA_256(request, without SS).\n           f.  Then, the receiver retrieves the public key of the senderId from the DB and reverse engineer the signature field to output HS = Verify(SS, Sender's Public Key)\n           g. If HR (Hash done by Receiver) and HS (Hash sent by sender) matches, the signature is valid and it is indeed the sender who is owner of the request.\n           h. Imposter behavior - If the sender signs a request and an imposter adds data in the request while in transit, the hash done by the \n               receiver on the request (HR) will not match the reverse engineering of the signature using the sender's public key (HS) and hence the receiver will reject the request.\n           i. In short, the receiver hashed on compromised request (HR) and reverse engineering of the signature outputs sender's hash (HS) and both will not match .\n     3. Encrypting a request means nobody apart from the sender and receiver can know the raw form of the request.\n           a. It ensures privacy and confidentiality.\n           b. When Sender and Receiver first meet, the Receiver generates a private key and public key for encryption and forwards the public key to the sender. This is exactly \n               opposite of Signing.\n           c. Once sender adds a signature field to the request, it generates a random private key and encrypts the request using the private key SR = Encrypt(Request, Private Key)\n           d. Post that, the sender uses the receiver's public key to encrypt the Private Key generated SK = Encrypt(Private Key, Receiver's Public Key) and then prepares the request\n               {\"senderId\":{}, \"encrypted_payload\": \"SR\", \"encrypted_key\": \"SK\"}\n           e. Receiver uses its own private key and decrypts the \"encrypted_key\" to output sender's private key = Decrypt(encrypted_key, Receiver's private key)\n           f. Post that, it uses the private key to decrypt \"encrypted_payload\" to output the request with signature --> Request = Decrypt(encrypted_payload, sender's private key )\n           g. Once the request is in its raw form with \"Signature\" field, it follows the signature protocol to verify the signature.\n    4. You may notice that in Encryption, we used 2 layers of encryption but in Signing, we used 1 layer of encryption.\n           a. The second layer of Encryption in Encryption and 1st layer of Encryption in Signing is called Asymmetric Encryption (RSA) \n               which is fast for slower payload and slow for larger payload.\n           b. Hence, we have 1st layer of encryption in Encryption and Hashing in Signing to shorten the payload. The 1st layer of encryption in encryption is called Symmetric \n              Encryption (AES) which is fast for shorter payload and Hashing using SHA_256 is also fast.\n           c. In Signing, you don't need 2 layers of encryption because we hash the request and then signs/encrypt the request and just adds a signature field to the request.\n               So, technically, we are sending the whole request in raw form to the receiver.\n           d. However, in encryption, if you hash and then apply encrypt, there is no way the receiver can un-hash it as hashing is one way and the request cannot be seen in its raw form.\n    5. In problems where a request needs an expiry timestamp, an impostor can periodically replay the request multiple times until the request is deemed expired by the receiver.\n        In such scenarios, the receiver should own the responsibility of idempotency and the sender should own the responsibility of providing a unique identifier (called nonce)\n    6. The keys needs to be rotated. So, the responsibility falls on the owner who creates the key (Sender for signing and Receiver for encryption). The owner needs to gain confidence\n         on the new keys. So, it will send a KeyVersionId to the receiver know which version of the key to use for signing and encryption. Once enough confidence is built, new key becomes\n         primary and delete old key. In scenarios where confidence is not built yet but new key fails, receiver can deny the request. The sender should fallback to old key and use old key\n         version id to process the request (which was denied due to system issue) and the receiver can use the old key to validate the request. IF the new key hits a failure threshold,\n         discard and generate a new one.\n    7.  Sensitive data such as Keys cannot be stored in system's business database. It can have own secluded database such that if the business database is compromised, the keys should\n          remain safe.\n    8. Additionally, sensitive data such as Credit Card needs to be tokenized (with false values) using TokenServiceProvider which maps the random token values to the credit card.\n        The system can persist token values in place of credit card number and use that to communicate with the bank. Bank also have access to TSP to validate which card to charge.\n        In short, sensitive data will have 3 pillars - Signing+Encryption+Tokenization(At Server)\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
